WEBVTT

00:19.269 --> 00:20.429
[CHIRPING]

00:21.355 --> 00:23.141
[SQUAWKS]

00:30.030 --> 00:31.645
[SQUAWKING]

00:41.750 --> 00:42.956
[SHOVEL THUMPS]

01:11.196 --> 01:12.857
LINDA:
Duke?

01:13.532 --> 01:15.193
DUKE:
Testing our accommodations.

01:15.409 --> 01:17.400
Well, sorry to bother you,
but Sam Verdreaux called.

01:17.619 --> 01:18.654
He sounded good and sauced,

01:18.870 --> 01:21.122
but he wants us to know
that he heard some kind of a bang.

01:21.331 --> 01:22.707
Like a car backfired?

01:23.417 --> 01:26.534
Or a bang like Tommy Anderson
finally shot his wife?

01:27.588 --> 01:28.919
He didn't specify.

01:29.131 --> 01:31.838
But Sam's the only one that called it in
so I didn't wanna overreact.

01:32.050 --> 01:33.551
No.

01:33.927 --> 01:35.542
You were right to get me, Linda.

01:37.973 --> 01:39.804
You never know
with this damn place.

01:40.017 --> 01:41.507
[DOOR BELLS CHIMING]

01:48.150 --> 01:49.981
You off to the game today, Big Jim?

01:50.193 --> 01:51.729
No, I'm sitting this one out, actually.

01:51.945 --> 01:56.359
Oh. I thought the whole town council
always rode that stupid float together.

01:56.575 --> 01:57.781
[JIM CHUCKLES]

01:57.993 --> 02:03.454
Working the lot today,
so the guys let me sit this one out.

02:03.665 --> 02:06.122
Heavy is the head
that wears many hats.

02:06.335 --> 02:08.872
I'm not sure
that's quite how that one goes.

02:09.713 --> 02:12.750
We're having a big sale
on our pre-owns.

02:13.925 --> 02:16.507
Hoping we're a little busier than here,
no offense.

02:16.720 --> 02:17.960
Sunday mornings have been brutal

02:18.180 --> 02:20.091
since they opened that Denny's
over in Westlake.

02:20.307 --> 02:23.470
I'll take your French toast
any day of the week, Rose.

02:27.064 --> 02:30.522
- Jim, what is this?
- That's me buying your next vote.

02:30.734 --> 02:33.100
Says the guy who
always runs unopposed.

02:34.029 --> 02:35.565
We're all in this together.

02:35.906 --> 02:37.567
[PANTING]

02:41.620 --> 02:43.281
God.

02:44.122 --> 02:45.828
I know, right?

02:46.041 --> 02:47.781
[BOTH PANTING]

02:48.001 --> 02:49.912
No, you don't.

02:56.468 --> 02:58.254
- Angie.
- Huh?

03:02.599 --> 03:03.964
I love you.

03:06.186 --> 03:07.926
Yeah.

03:08.355 --> 03:10.687
It's been a fun summer.

03:14.444 --> 03:17.231
- Ouch.
- Junior, we both know what this is.

03:17.447 --> 03:19.563
And you go back to school
in a few days.

03:19.950 --> 03:22.066
JUNIOR:
No, I'm not.

03:22.285 --> 03:24.241
I'm dropping out.

03:24.454 --> 03:25.660
I dropped out, I'm done.

03:26.415 --> 03:28.827
- Are you insane?
- You've never been.

03:29.042 --> 03:32.910
Trust me, college is just another
lame-ass pyramid scheme.

03:33.296 --> 03:36.333
They hand you a free ride out of this
place, and you just throw it away?

03:36.550 --> 03:38.461
- This is about us. This is not about--
- Please don't.

03:38.677 --> 03:41.919
No, Angie, just listen to me
for a second, all right?

03:42.973 --> 03:45.715
Hey, hey, hey. Hey.

03:47.978 --> 03:50.344
l have loved you
since the third grade.

03:52.691 --> 03:56.650
You're the only person in the whole
world who knows the real me.

03:59.489 --> 04:01.650
And that's why I can't be with you.

04:02.617 --> 04:04.608
Look, I'm gonna be late for work.

04:04.828 --> 04:06.034
Why are you acting like this?

04:08.123 --> 04:10.114
- Hey.
- Ow!

04:39.571 --> 04:41.436
JULIA:
Mrs. Grinnell?

04:41.782 --> 04:43.989
Julia Shumway.

04:44.701 --> 04:47.192
You wanted to see me in person?

04:47.412 --> 04:49.198
So you're the newspaper woman?

04:49.414 --> 04:52.281
I'm the new editor
of The Independent, yeah.

04:52.501 --> 04:54.662
If you're having a problem
with your delivery, you can--

04:54.878 --> 04:58.211
| get my news online, sweetheart,
like everybody else.

04:58.673 --> 05:01.540
I called you because I got a tip.

05:01.885 --> 05:02.920
About what?

05:03.720 --> 05:05.756
See that truck?

05:05.972 --> 05:09.089
That's its fourth propane delivery
this week.

05:09.309 --> 05:11.641
Last week, it made six.

05:11.853 --> 05:15.061
Looks like someone's planning
one hell of a barbecue.

05:15.273 --> 05:16.353
Or:

05:16.566 --> 05:17.897
[IMITATES EXPLOSION]

05:18.819 --> 05:20.650
You think this might be connected
to terrorism?

05:20.862 --> 05:24.320
Like they say,
"See something, say something."

05:24.533 --> 05:26.023
Why tell me? Why not the police?

05:26.243 --> 05:28.484
I called Sheriff Perkins
three days ago.

05:28.703 --> 05:32.366
He said he'd look into it.
Turns out everything's above board.

05:33.041 --> 05:37.455
Town hall is just restocking
its emergency reserves.

05:37.671 --> 05:39.753
Here's the thing.

05:40.048 --> 05:43.256
When Duke told me,
he sounded nervous.

05:44.886 --> 05:49.471
Believe me, that man's never
sounded nervous a day in his life.

05:52.310 --> 05:54.141
Okay.

05:57.440 --> 05:59.431
I'll do some digging.

05:59.651 --> 06:00.686
[CAMERA CLICKING]

06:00.902 --> 06:02.733
Whatever you find,

06:03.488 --> 06:06.571
you leave my name the hell out of it.

06:35.729 --> 06:37.515
Where the hell are they taking
all our trucks?

06:37.731 --> 06:38.891
Over to Westlake, it's parade day.

06:39.107 --> 06:40.142
[TRUCK HORN HONKING]

06:40.358 --> 06:42.269
I love you too, Rusty.

06:42.485 --> 06:44.066
[TRUCK HORN HONKING]

06:45.113 --> 06:47.900
DUKE: I'll never understand why you
said yes to one of those meatheads.

06:48.116 --> 06:51.358
Because their insurance policy
makes ours look like crap.

06:52.621 --> 06:56.580
No. I'm headed back now.
Hey, listen, so we got a problem here.

06:56.791 --> 07:00.534
Your guy Smith shows up,
he doesn't have the money

07:00.754 --> 07:04.997
and then he tries to renegotiate,
aggressively.

07:07.135 --> 07:08.841
Hey. I gotta call you back.

07:14.684 --> 07:17.221
Incoming. No front tag.

07:17.437 --> 07:20.144
This is 102.
Can you run a plate for us?

07:20.857 --> 07:23.018
Boy-Adam-Boy, 162.

07:36.831 --> 07:38.958
[SCREAMS
AND TIRES SCREECHES]

07:42.796 --> 07:44.411
[cows MOOING]

08:03.191 --> 08:04.226
Perfect.

08:13.618 --> 08:14.858
[RUMBUNG]

08:15.078 --> 08:16.864
[CROWS SQUAWKING]

08:22.961 --> 08:25.077
[RUMBLING CONTINUES]

08:26.381 --> 08:28.372
[RUMBLING
AND CAR ALARM RINGING]

08:31.428 --> 08:32.463
MAN:
Whoa. Hey, guys, wait.

08:34.723 --> 08:36.714
[RUMBLING
AND CHURCH BELL RINGING]

08:41.688 --> 08:43.770
[RUMBLING CONTINUES]

08:54.325 --> 08:55.940
[DUKE GRUNTS
AND TIRES SCREECHING]

08:56.161 --> 08:57.446
Unh!

08:58.371 --> 08:59.406
Duke.

09:04.294 --> 09:06.000
[THUMP]

09:06.212 --> 09:07.793
[cows MOOING]

09:45.210 --> 09:46.825
[ELECTRICITY ZAPS
AND BARBIE GRUNTS]

10:09.442 --> 10:10.773
[DOME HUMMING]

10:36.761 --> 10:38.547
[FLIES BUZZING]

10:42.767 --> 10:43.802
JOE:
You okay?

10:46.980 --> 10:49.437
I saw your car spin out.

10:50.483 --> 10:52.144
What happened?

10:55.155 --> 10:56.190
Wow.

10:58.783 --> 10:59.898
Hey. No, don't touch that.

11:00.118 --> 11:01.358
[ELECTRICITY ZAPS
AND JOE GASPS]

11:01.578 --> 11:03.785
Holy crap.

11:05.915 --> 11:06.950
What is it?

11:11.796 --> 11:13.661
What the hell?

11:16.509 --> 11:18.170
- Are you sure you're okay, Duke?
- Yeah.

11:18.761 --> 11:21.218
My damn pacemaker,
must've skipped a beat.

11:21.931 --> 11:23.432
That's supposed
to make me feel better?

11:23.641 --> 11:25.097
I'm fine.

11:25.310 --> 11:26.971
WOMAN [OVER RADIO]:
We have a problem here.

11:27.187 --> 11:29.143
- All our landlines are dead.
- Okay.

11:29.355 --> 11:31.346
FREDDY: Freddy here.
PAUL: Paul here.

11:32.108 --> 11:33.973
One at a time, geniuses.
Freddy, you go first.

11:34.944 --> 11:38.277
FREDDY: Sorry, Duke. We've got
a downed power line over by the clinic.

11:38.489 --> 11:39.524
Paul?

11:39.741 --> 11:42.699
PAUL: Same story across town at
the Food Mart. Sparks and everything.

11:42.911 --> 11:44.572
What could cause that?

11:44.787 --> 11:45.822
A twister?

11:46.039 --> 11:47.825
[AIRPLANE APPROACHING]

11:51.419 --> 11:52.625
[DOME HUMMING]

11:55.048 --> 11:56.254
[DOME HUMMING]

11:56.466 --> 11:58.673
It's some sort of invisible fence.

11:59.260 --> 12:00.761
Like those ones for dogs.

12:03.765 --> 12:05.175
It only zaps you the first time.

12:05.391 --> 12:09.134
It's like some sort of
static electricity or...

12:10.980 --> 12:12.231
[BIRD THUMPS]

12:16.694 --> 12:17.729
BARBIE:
Necks are snapped.

12:18.529 --> 12:20.144
This thing must be crazy high.

12:20.490 --> 12:22.355
[AIRPLANE APPROACHING]

12:34.587 --> 12:37.329
Go! Run! Run!

12:42.637 --> 12:44.798
What the hell is happening?

12:46.432 --> 12:48.047
JIM: God Almighty,
what are we looking at?

12:48.476 --> 12:51.058
MAN: Looks like a prop plane
just exploded in midair.

12:52.063 --> 12:53.928
A plane crash?

12:54.649 --> 12:56.514
In Chester's Mill?

12:57.026 --> 12:58.562
[TIRES SCREECHING]

13:04.325 --> 13:07.988
JOE: Is your phone getting any service?
- I have nothing.

13:14.210 --> 13:15.245
Let me see that.

13:22.385 --> 13:25.718
It's Mrs. Sanders, from the bank.

13:26.014 --> 13:27.675
She sponsored
our Little League team.

13:34.397 --> 13:36.979
BARBIE:
No,no,no.Hey!

13:37.567 --> 13:39.558
Hey! Stop the truck!

13:39.777 --> 13:42.359
JOE: If it crashes through, you're dead.
- Stop! Stop!

13:43.531 --> 13:44.566
Stop the truck!

13:46.200 --> 13:47.280
Stop!

13:52.749 --> 13:54.785
Why can't we hear the sirens?

13:55.001 --> 13:56.832
No, no, no, stop!

13:58.296 --> 14:02.665
- What are you doing?
- Telling them to call the FAA.

14:02.884 --> 14:04.840
- The feds?
- Yes.

14:05.053 --> 14:07.214
They gotta shut down
this whole airspace.

14:07.430 --> 14:09.796
JOE: Okay, what if the government
built this thing?

14:11.517 --> 14:12.552
I doubt it.

14:13.686 --> 14:15.301
Why?

14:16.272 --> 14:18.513
Because it works.

14:18.983 --> 14:20.018
[CLICK]

14:20.860 --> 14:22.270
[GENERATOR HUMMING]

14:22.487 --> 14:24.068
PHIL [OVER RADIO]:
Sorry for the radio silence, folks.

14:24.280 --> 14:26.271
Generator's cooking
and we ’re up and running again.

14:26.491 --> 14:29.574
I'm Phil Bushey,
and you're listening to WYBS,

14:29.786 --> 14:35.201
the Mill's only 100 percent
independent home of rock.

14:35.416 --> 14:36.997
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING]

14:37.210 --> 14:39.075
- Phil.
- Dodee, hey.

14:39.295 --> 14:42.913
We're the only thing on air right now,
AM, FM, anywhere.

14:43.132 --> 14:44.247
Yeah, the blackout, I know.

14:44.467 --> 14:45.752
No, even if that were statewide,

14:45.968 --> 14:48.300
every station our size has
its own generator,

14:49.097 --> 14:50.803
so why is the whole dial still static?

14:51.015 --> 14:52.846
I don't know.

14:53.476 --> 14:57.014
But our ratings are gonna
be amazing.

15:05.238 --> 15:06.728
DUKE:
What the hell happened here?

15:06.948 --> 15:08.438
Sheriff Perkins.

15:08.658 --> 15:11.149
The plane smashed right into it.
I was almost killed.

15:11.369 --> 15:13.906
- This man saved my life.
DUKE: Slow down, son. Slow down.

15:15.123 --> 15:16.829
You hurt?

15:17.458 --> 15:20.040
No, I think something just clipped me
on the way down.

15:21.295 --> 15:23.331
LINDA: Why aren't the guys putting
out the fires?

15:23.548 --> 15:25.960
You saw it crash. Into what?

15:26.384 --> 15:30.252
I don't know, but, I mean,
whatever this thing is, it is big.

15:30.471 --> 15:33.178
JOE:
It's like a wall, you just can't see it.

15:33.391 --> 15:35.302
Rusty.

15:35.518 --> 15:37.258
- Rusty.
- I don't think he can hear you.

15:37.687 --> 15:38.722
God.

15:41.399 --> 15:43.060
Baby, you okay?

15:44.193 --> 15:46.445
RUSTY:
I can't hear you.

15:50.992 --> 15:53.108
- Step away from there, Linda.
- I don't understand.

15:53.494 --> 15:54.654
What is it?

16:02.128 --> 16:03.459
Watch your step, Jim.

16:03.671 --> 16:05.411
That's Chuck Thomson's plane,
isn't it?

16:06.507 --> 16:08.008
Not anymore.

16:08.217 --> 16:09.468
PAUL [OVER RADIO]:
Hey, Duke?

16:09.677 --> 16:11.508
We got a real bad accident
on Pretty Valley.

16:11.929 --> 16:14.671
FREDDY: Duke, it's Freddy.
I’ve got one too, over on Motton.

16:14.891 --> 16:19.260
A minivan versus... I don't know what,
but the thing’s flat as a dime.

16:19.479 --> 16:21.845
Whole family's DOA.

16:22.064 --> 16:25.556
Whatever it is, it cut off all our roads.

16:26.402 --> 16:28.563
Not just the roads,

16:29.822 --> 16:31.232
the whole town.

16:35.703 --> 16:37.364
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

16:38.206 --> 16:40.071
We're trapped.

16:46.380 --> 16:47.540
JIM:
Okay, here's what we got.

16:47.757 --> 16:50.248
There's 19 roads going in and out
of Chester's Mill.

16:50.468 --> 16:51.583
Not including the dirt ones.

16:51.802 --> 16:53.338
Joe, would you go home
and stay there?

16:53.554 --> 16:56.762
DUKE: Paul and Freddy are setting up
roadblocks here and over here,

16:56.974 --> 16:59.010
but it's gonna take time
to button up the whole town.

16:59.227 --> 17:01.684
Do what you can.
I got a contingency plan.

17:03.022 --> 17:04.603
No, no, no, Julia.
This is a crime scene.

17:04.815 --> 17:06.897
JULIA: No. Plane falls out of the sky,
that's news.

17:07.109 --> 17:09.486
I'm the ranking official here,
and I'm ordering you to leave.

17:09.695 --> 17:10.980
Jim. We got bigger fish to fry.

17:11.197 --> 17:13.028
Linda, you commandeer
Ms. Shumway's vehicle.

17:13.324 --> 17:16.908
- We'll cover more ground splitting up.
JULIA: What the hell? That's my car.

17:21.415 --> 17:23.406
[SIREN WAILING]

17:31.133 --> 17:32.168
Who the hell are you?

17:36.138 --> 17:37.878
Barbie.

17:38.891 --> 17:40.597
People just call me Barbie.

17:41.519 --> 17:42.554
Barbie?

17:42.979 --> 17:44.059
It's a nickname.

17:44.272 --> 17:46.012
Anyway, I'm not your story.

17:47.817 --> 17:49.227
Then why don't you Show me
what is?

17:52.196 --> 17:53.481
[DINGING]

17:56.075 --> 17:58.817
- Am I doing something wrong?
- Power's out, Carolyn.

17:59.036 --> 18:00.742
Cashier said the pumps
will be back on soon.

18:00.955 --> 18:05.540
"Chester's Mill is known for its rich,
fertile land and warm, inviting people."

18:05.918 --> 18:07.954
Please, these jerks don't
even have orange juice.

18:08.170 --> 18:10.126
Guy said we'd have to wait
till the next delivery.

18:10.339 --> 18:13.251
Alice, you didn't take your insulin
without eating.

18:13.467 --> 18:15.594
I'll be fine. I got a candy bar.

18:15.803 --> 18:18.419
No. You need real food, honey.

18:19.515 --> 18:21.051
We'll stop at that diner we passed.

18:21.267 --> 18:23.508
Mom, seriously, can we please drive
somewhere else?

18:23.728 --> 18:25.184
I refuse to have my last meal here.

18:25.396 --> 18:28.604
Norrie, you're not going to your
execution, you're going to camp.

18:28.816 --> 18:32.104
Camp? It's like a glorified prison
for screw-ups with rich parents.

18:32.320 --> 18:34.060
It's a great program, Norrie.

18:34.280 --> 18:37.397
And as soon as they say you're ready,
you can come home again.

18:37.617 --> 18:40.279
Los AngeleS. Awesome.

18:40.828 --> 18:42.864
[TIRES SCREECHING
AND SIREN WAILING]

18:48.544 --> 18:49.875
We can stop for lunch later.

18:56.552 --> 18:57.792
[DOME HUMMING]

19:00.598 --> 19:04.432
JULIA: Where the hell did it come from?
- I have no idea.

19:04.935 --> 19:08.427
If thiS thing just appeared
out of thin air,

19:08.648 --> 19:10.980
you think maybe it'll disappear too?

19:11.609 --> 19:13.645
Yeah, maybe.

19:15.988 --> 19:17.273
[DOME HUMMING]

19:19.241 --> 19:22.074
You think we might be stuck
in here a while.

19:23.996 --> 19:27.329
I think that even if what's wrong
suddenly becomes right,

19:27.541 --> 19:29.998
the Army's gonna
quarantine this place.

19:30.211 --> 19:31.371
So you're military, huh?

19:32.338 --> 19:34.420
Not recently.

19:44.225 --> 19:46.056
WOMAN:
Help me.

19:47.687 --> 19:50.144
Help me. Help me.

19:53.359 --> 19:55.315
JULIA: How did she--?
- She must've been reaching across

19:55.528 --> 19:56.563
when that thing came down.

19:56.779 --> 20:00.146
It's okay. My husband's a doctor.
We're gonna get you to the hospital.

20:02.243 --> 20:05.110
I can't even grab
a regular broadcast signal.

20:05.329 --> 20:08.071
Phil, something bad is going on
out there, okay?

20:08.290 --> 20:10.952
It could be solar flares
disrupting the entire grid.

20:11.168 --> 20:14.581
Dodee, the cable is out,
it doesn't mean it's the end times.

20:14.797 --> 20:17.789
When packs of mutants start swarming
this place, don't say I didn't warn you.

20:18.008 --> 20:19.043
[BANGING ON DOOR]

20:19.260 --> 20:21.467
Hey! ThiS iS Councilman Rennie!
Open the damn door!

20:21.679 --> 20:24.591
PHIL: I'm not supposed to let anyone
inside while we're broad--

20:24.932 --> 20:27.389
What the hell? You better have
a warrant or we're gonna sue--

20:27.601 --> 20:29.808
You're gonna let me make an
emergency broadcast right now

20:30.020 --> 20:31.271
or someone's gonna die.

20:33.232 --> 20:35.314
[SOFT ROCK MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKERS]

20:37.319 --> 20:39.401
[SOFT ROCK MUSIC CONTINUES
PLAYING OVER RADIO]

20:50.332 --> 20:52.789
JIM [ON RADIO]:
This is an emergency broadcast,

20:53.002 --> 20:55.664
so please pay careful attention.

20:55.880 --> 20:59.088
My name is Councilman Rennie.
Big Jim Rennie.

20:59.300 --> 21:01.291
But this isn’t a car commercial.

21:01.510 --> 21:03.922
Please stop what you’re doing
and listen.

21:04.555 --> 21:07.092
We have a serious situation in town
and it's very important

21:07.308 --> 21:12.644
that every driver listening to my voice
stops their vehicle now.

21:15.524 --> 21:17.981
- You're the one who's addicted.
- I use my phone for work,

21:18.194 --> 21:20.401
not for sending naked pictures
of myself to random boys.

21:20.613 --> 21:22.353
For the millionth time,
that was an accident.

21:22.573 --> 21:25.736
That's what you said
when you knocked out that girl's tooth.

21:27.203 --> 21:30.661
JIM: Once again, every car needs
to pull over immediately.

21:30.873 --> 21:32.488
This is not a drill.

21:32.708 --> 21:33.743
Did you hear that?

21:33.959 --> 21:38.077
I can't tell you if what happened
is an act of terror or an act of God,

21:38.297 --> 21:40.333
but I'll keep everyone updated
as we learn more.

21:40.549 --> 21:42.460
It's just some stupid
viral marketing thing, Mom.

21:43.719 --> 21:47.382
Norrie's right. There are other people
on the road. It's probably some stunt--

21:48.516 --> 21:49.801
[ALL SCREAMING]

21:50.017 --> 21:51.097
[TIRES SCREECHING]

21:59.944 --> 22:01.434
ALICE:
ls everyone all right?

22:02.488 --> 22:04.194
CAROLYN:
No.

22:04.990 --> 22:07.242
Nothing about this

22:07.576 --> 22:08.861
is all right.

22:12.873 --> 22:15.910
ALICE: Norrie?
- Norrie. Are you okay?

22:17.086 --> 22:21.546
ALICE: Keep her head up.
- The pink stars are falling.

22:22.883 --> 22:28.674
The pink stars are falling in lines.

22:29.223 --> 22:32.260
The pink stars are falling in lines.

22:35.437 --> 22:37.018
Mom?

22:37.231 --> 22:40.018
- Ange, where the hell is Mom?
- You're the one who lives here.

22:40.234 --> 22:41.815
- Where's Dad?
- Still on the road.

22:42.027 --> 22:45.736
You're sure? A guy at the diner said
there might've been a chemical spill.

22:45.948 --> 22:50.442
l was worried it was Dad's truck,
I came here as fast as I could.

22:52.621 --> 22:53.656
Joe, what is it?

22:53.873 --> 22:56.114
Mom's having brunch
with Uncle Steve at Denny's.

22:56.667 --> 22:58.953
- And?
- Angie, Denny's is in Westlake.

22:59.169 --> 23:01.876
- So, what?
- That's on the other Side of this thing.

23:02.840 --> 23:04.501
We're on our own.

23:07.136 --> 23:08.922
[TRUCK HORN HONKING
AND SIREN WAILING]

23:09.138 --> 23:10.924
MAN 1:
Coming through. Clear.

23:11.140 --> 23:13.597
MAN 2: I need help over here.
MAN 1: Clear.

23:14.977 --> 23:16.513
MAN 3:
Let's go.

23:17.062 --> 23:19.599
MAN 4:
Fracture over here, guys.

23:20.983 --> 23:23.190
Ms. Shumway? Thank God.
Is the doc with you?

23:23.402 --> 23:25.939
He's not here?
Peter always works Sundays.

23:26.155 --> 23:28.111
Your husband hasn't worked
Sundays in weeks.

23:32.036 --> 23:35.278
He probably just went home.
I Should go check on him.

23:38.250 --> 23:39.410
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

23:39.710 --> 23:41.166
MAN 1:
Has the governor contacted you?

23:41.378 --> 23:44.120
MAN 2: We just need some answers.
MAN 3: What's caused this?

23:47.009 --> 23:49.091
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

24:14.870 --> 24:17.361
WOMAN:
We need a wheelchair over here.

24:18.791 --> 24:20.452
[LIGHTER CLICKING]

24:21.669 --> 24:23.910
WOMAN: Good. Exactly what we need.
MAN: A little help?

24:24.129 --> 24:26.211
Can I burn one?

24:27.591 --> 24:29.047
Yeah.

24:31.470 --> 24:33.131
A little young to be a nurse,
aren't you?

24:33.347 --> 24:36.089
Just a lowly candy striper.

24:44.775 --> 24:46.390
So you saw whatever did all this?

24:47.403 --> 24:49.519
I mean, what there is to see, yeah.

24:49.738 --> 24:55.278
Some of the patients are saying
it'S like we're stuck in a giant fishbowl.

24:57.913 --> 25:00.199
I used to have fish.

25:02.376 --> 25:03.912
Goldfish. Heh, heh.

25:07.423 --> 25:11.007
But then one of them got Sick,
and the other one...

25:12.428 --> 25:14.464
The other one ate him.

25:16.015 --> 25:20.258
Did you even know they did that?
Goldfish?

25:22.354 --> 25:23.935
Want something for that?

25:31.071 --> 25:32.652
I just wanna get out of here.

25:32.865 --> 25:34.651
Yeah.

25:35.034 --> 25:36.865
You and me both.

25:42.166 --> 25:43.406
CAROLYN:
Help.

25:43.625 --> 25:45.240
Please, we need help.

25:45.461 --> 25:47.668
Our daughter's had
some sort of episode.

25:47.880 --> 25:49.586
It was a damn seizure, Alice.

25:50.090 --> 25:52.126
ANGIE:
Come on, let's get her looked at.

25:52.468 --> 25:53.503
Watch your head.

25:55.429 --> 25:57.670
All right. All right.

25:57.890 --> 26:00.131
Just go in right there.

26:22.498 --> 26:23.783
Looks like a ghost town in here.

26:23.999 --> 26:26.706
JIM: Yeah, no word from anyone else
on the council yet,

26:26.919 --> 26:28.625
but I Should be able
to hold down the fort.

26:28.837 --> 26:29.997
It's easier to reach consensus

26:30.214 --> 26:33.672
when there's only one voice
to listen to, right? Heh, heh, heh.

26:34.343 --> 26:36.379
Anyway, I appreciate what you did
on the radio today.

26:36.595 --> 26:39.632
- You saved some lives.
- Just doing my job and all.

26:39.848 --> 26:40.883
How your men holding up?

26:41.100 --> 26:44.558
We're Spread thin Since most of them
were at that damn parade,

26:44.812 --> 26:45.847
but we'll soldier on.

26:46.063 --> 26:47.303
Well, for now you will,

26:47.523 --> 26:51.311
but what happens if this thing lasts
for days or weeks?

26:51.527 --> 26:54.064
Well, we might need more manpower
to maintain the peace.

26:55.322 --> 26:56.482
What are you getting at, Jim?

26:56.698 --> 26:59.155
Well, during emergencies,
councilmen have the power

26:59.368 --> 27:01.825
to authorize additional police officers.

27:02.037 --> 27:05.325
The last thing this mess needs
is amateurs with badges.

27:05.541 --> 27:08.453
Till I hear othenNise,
from the mayor or above,

27:08.669 --> 27:10.000
you're not authorizing anything.

27:12.047 --> 27:13.912
Understood.

27:14.341 --> 27:15.877
Good.

27:17.719 --> 27:21.086
What do we do when the people start
asking about the propane?

27:22.808 --> 27:25.720
- Well, that has nothing to do with this.
- Oh, I know that.

27:25.936 --> 27:27.892
But some people might find it
hard to swallow

27:28.105 --> 27:32.018
that we just happened to be stockpiling
fuel right before a disaster.

27:35.195 --> 27:37.572
- So should we tell them the truth?
- That's your business.

27:38.490 --> 27:40.731
I had no idea what the hell you wanted
with all that crap.

27:40.951 --> 27:41.986
Oh.

27:42.202 --> 27:43.908
[LAUGHS]

27:44.371 --> 27:46.236
Please,

27:46.915 --> 27:50.032
you were more than happy
to turn a blind eye,

27:50.377 --> 27:52.618
but you're not dumb.

27:54.089 --> 27:57.877
I did what I had to do to keep this town
from going broke, to keep it safe.

27:58.093 --> 28:00.505
Ooh. Careful, Duke.

28:00.721 --> 28:02.052
You don't wanna put
too much stress

28:02.264 --> 28:04.801
on that bum ticker of yours now,
do you?

28:05.392 --> 28:06.427
Are you threatening me?

28:06.643 --> 28:08.929
Oh, just reminding you

28:09.354 --> 28:11.436
what the lay of the land is.

28:16.028 --> 28:17.984
We're all in this together.

28:23.452 --> 28:26.785
Regular receivers can't pull a signal
through whatever haS cut uS off,

28:26.997 --> 28:29.283
but I once used our broadcast tower
like a giant antenna

28:29.499 --> 28:31.410
to pull feedback loops
for my band's cover album.

28:31.627 --> 28:34.334
Dodee, just tell me what you heard.

28:36.298 --> 28:37.959
DODEE:
This.

28:38.258 --> 28:41.091
[INDISTINCT NOISES OVER RADIO]

28:41.303 --> 28:43.168
Sounds alien?

28:44.973 --> 28:46.088
Sounds like Bjork.

28:46.975 --> 28:48.636
It comes and goes like that.

28:48.852 --> 28:51.514
Sometimes its music, sometimes
cell phone conversations. ltjust...

28:51.730 --> 28:53.721
MAN:
Army Corps of Engineers’ best guess

28:53.941 --> 28:55.647
puts the dome over Chester's Mill

28:55.859 --> 28:58.350
at roughly 20,000 feet...

28:58.570 --> 28:59.776
[INDISTINCT NOISES
OVER RADIO]

28:59.988 --> 29:01.728
Did he just call it a dome?

29:03.116 --> 29:04.777
Yeah.

29:15.170 --> 29:16.751
[TWIGS RUSTLING]

29:16.964 --> 29:19.876
JUNIOR: Sorry. I didn't mean
to sneak up on you like that.

29:20.133 --> 29:21.919
I'm Junior.

29:27.349 --> 29:28.885
Hey, um,

29:29.351 --> 29:31.216
do we know each other?

29:32.062 --> 29:35.179
BARBIE: Doubt it.
- You sure?

29:36.191 --> 29:38.853
I don't know, something about you
just looks so familiar.

29:41.113 --> 29:42.148
[JUNIOR WHISTLES]

29:42.364 --> 29:43.695
I'm talking to you, dumbass.

29:45.033 --> 29:46.898
Look,

29:47.119 --> 29:50.828
I don't know what I did to piSS you off,
but I promise you,

29:51.039 --> 29:53.451
you don't wanna
start something here.

29:55.377 --> 29:57.538
What if I do?

29:59.006 --> 30:00.542
[CAR DOOR OPENING]

30:01.550 --> 30:04.917
JULIA: Everything all right out here?
JUNIOR: Hey, Mrs. S.

30:05.137 --> 30:06.172
BARBIE:
Yeah.

30:06.763 --> 30:08.628
Everyone's been very welcoming.

30:12.436 --> 30:14.222
JUNIOR:
Be seeing you.

30:25.991 --> 30:30.030
- What the hell waS that about?
- I have no idea.

30:31.371 --> 30:32.531
Any word from your husband?

30:34.166 --> 30:36.077
He wasn't back home,

30:36.626 --> 30:39.242
so now I've been checking
all the roadblocks.

30:41.673 --> 30:43.504
This was the last one.

30:43.759 --> 30:46.296
At least he wasn't
one of the crashes.

30:50.098 --> 30:51.679
What about you?

30:51.975 --> 30:53.010
Where you off to?

30:54.394 --> 30:58.387
The motels are all booked up,
so I'm just gonna rough it.

31:00.025 --> 31:01.606
Don't be ridiculous.

31:01.818 --> 31:04.025
- You can stay with Peter and me.
- No, no, no--

31:04.237 --> 31:06.523
Linda said
you saved a kid's life today.

31:06.907 --> 31:10.149
I'm not about to let you Sleep out here
like an animal.

31:14.289 --> 31:17.122
Come on. I insist.

31:36.520 --> 31:38.431
[HIP HOP MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKERS]

31:38.647 --> 31:39.682
GIRL:
Party.

31:39.898 --> 31:42.014
[CHATTERING]

31:44.111 --> 31:45.521
BEN:
McAlister.

31:46.113 --> 31:49.731
- It's Ben. Ben Drake from AP English.
- Hey, man.

31:49.950 --> 31:51.986
Hey, so iS it true,
are you seriously home alone?

31:53.120 --> 31:55.611
Man, your house parties
are gonna be Sick.

32:00.168 --> 32:02.204
BEN: So have you touched
the force-field thing?

32:02.796 --> 32:04.752
Whatley says it's straight out
of Star Trek.

32:06.425 --> 32:10.009
- You looking for something?
- Yeah, an off switch.

32:10.512 --> 32:13.754
This thing couldn't have
just appeared out of thin air.

32:13.974 --> 32:15.760
Whatever it is,

32:16.059 --> 32:17.890
it'S gotta have its own power source,
right?

32:18.562 --> 32:19.642
lguess.

32:19.855 --> 32:22.221
What if that power source
was somewhere in here with uS?

32:22.607 --> 32:27.021
Maybe it'S somewhere nearby,
distributing juice to the entire thing.

32:27.404 --> 32:28.860
Joe?

32:29.865 --> 32:31.105
Joe.

32:32.325 --> 32:34.452
JOE: The pink stars are falling.
- You all right, man?

32:34.661 --> 32:36.322
The pink stars are falling in lines.

32:36.538 --> 32:38.153
BEN:
Hey, let's get some help! Help!

32:38.373 --> 32:40.830
JOE: The pink stars are falling.
- Someone help! Get over here!

32:41.042 --> 32:43.294
JOE: The pink stars are falling in lines.
- Hey! Hey!

33:14.409 --> 33:15.819
[ANGIE SCREAMS]

33:16.036 --> 33:18.778
If you do everything I say,
I promise you won't get hurt, okay?

33:21.166 --> 33:25.125
ANGIE:
Help! Help! Help!

33:25.337 --> 33:26.417
[THUMP]

33:29.966 --> 33:31.547
Angie?

33:32.469 --> 33:34.255
I'm so sorry, Ange.

33:34.471 --> 33:35.881
I didn't want it to go like this.

33:55.659 --> 33:57.615
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

34:01.039 --> 34:02.825
[CHATTERING]

34:17.806 --> 34:21.048
DUKE:
I'm afraid I have some hard news.

34:22.310 --> 34:26.644
Some folks are still unaccounted for,
but it looks like Chester's Mill...

34:28.650 --> 34:30.106
lost 12 of her own today.

34:30.318 --> 34:31.899
[CROWD MURMURING]

34:34.155 --> 34:36.737
Duke, what the hell is going on?

34:36.950 --> 34:38.065
CAROLYN:
Isn't it obvious?

34:38.285 --> 34:40.617
- We're under attack.
- Nobody knows a damn thing,

34:40.829 --> 34:42.569
so there's no point
in Spreading any rumors.

34:42.789 --> 34:45.656
Please, our daughter iS sick.
We need to get her to a real doctor.

34:45.875 --> 34:48.036
I mean, even if they can't
knock that wall down,

34:48.253 --> 34:50.039
they can still airlift her out of here.

34:50.255 --> 34:53.213
I don't know, but if those eggheads
out there can drop a car on Mars,

34:53.425 --> 34:56.212
they sure as hell
can figure this out too.

34:56.636 --> 34:59.469
When everybody gets home tonight,
I want you to Check on your neighbors,

34:59.848 --> 35:04.592
and if anybody needs anything,
you know where to find me.

35:11.401 --> 35:12.766
[GROANS]

35:19.701 --> 35:21.066
[STAIRS CREAKING]

35:22.746 --> 35:24.077
[STAIRS CREAKING]

35:24.539 --> 35:25.779
[ANGIE GASPS]

35:29.544 --> 35:30.750
[DOOR CLANGING]

35:35.383 --> 35:36.839
Hey, Angie.

35:37.052 --> 35:40.135
Help! Somebody help me!

35:40.347 --> 35:41.632
Somebody help me!

35:41.848 --> 35:44.510
JUNIOR: Stop it. Quiet down. Stop.
- Oh, God, somebody please help me--

35:44.726 --> 35:46.387
Stop!

35:47.562 --> 35:49.348
Save your voice, babe.

35:49.564 --> 35:51.725
Okay? No one can hear us
all the way down here.

35:52.609 --> 35:53.724
Down?

35:54.235 --> 35:56.897
My dad's old fallout shelter.

35:57.739 --> 36:00.606
He's always been a little paranoid
about security,

36:01.117 --> 36:05.326
but you're safe now.

36:07.415 --> 36:10.657
- What are you talking about?
- I finally figured it out.

36:10.877 --> 36:14.995
Why you were acting so strange
this morning. It's all connected.

36:17.050 --> 36:19.416
I know how this must look,

36:19.636 --> 36:23.379
but I swear, in the long run,
you're gonna thank me for this.

36:26.142 --> 36:30.260
- Oh, my God. You've lost your mind.
- No, no.

36:30.772 --> 36:34.356
I'm the only person who understands
what's really going on around here.

36:35.985 --> 36:40.024
All I ask for is patience.

36:43.952 --> 36:47.490
Let go of me! Let go of me!

36:48.373 --> 36:52.787
Let me out of here!
Let me out! Let me out!

36:53.128 --> 36:54.368
[ANGIE SCREAMS]

36:54.879 --> 36:57.666
Junior! Ah!

37:05.306 --> 37:07.012
JIM:
Junior.

37:12.856 --> 37:14.517
Dad.

37:15.316 --> 37:17.898
- Where you been?
- Heard you on the radio.

37:18.111 --> 37:21.695
Sounded like we might need the old
shelter, but it's completely flooded.

37:21.906 --> 37:25.990
Oh, that's the least of our worries.
All that matters is you're okay.

37:27.579 --> 37:29.115
Whatever this is, I wanna help.

37:29.330 --> 37:31.867
I appreciate that,
but you got school--

37:32.083 --> 37:36.167
School's out there, I'm here,
and I wanna help.

38:09.370 --> 38:11.861
JULIA:
Honey, are you home?

38:18.171 --> 38:20.913
- How do you guys have power?
- Backup generator.

38:23.009 --> 38:26.297
Big Jim convinced my husband
it would be a tax write-off

38:26.513 --> 38:28.799
when we moved in here.

38:29.015 --> 38:31.301
That's Peter behind you.

38:50.912 --> 38:51.947
[SIGHS]

38:53.039 --> 38:54.370
You must think I'm an idiot.

38:59.838 --> 39:02.124
What do you mean?

39:05.093 --> 39:07.800
A journalist who doesn't know
what's going on under her own nose.

39:12.851 --> 39:14.682
I'm sure the whole town's thinking it.

39:18.690 --> 39:22.228
My husband isn't here
because he's having an affair.

39:35.290 --> 39:37.201
They don't know him like I do.

39:37.959 --> 39:39.540
He'll turn up, you'll see.

39:42.881 --> 39:44.963
I can't wait to meet him.

39:49.470 --> 39:51.006
Come on, I'll give you the nickel tour.

40:04.485 --> 40:08.273
l was supposed to be with Rusty today
at the game.

40:08.823 --> 40:11.781
Told him if we were ever gonna
afford a honeymoon,

40:11.993 --> 40:14.359
we both had to put in more overtime.

40:19.334 --> 40:20.665
[SIGHS]

40:21.044 --> 40:23.205
Why Chester's Mill?

40:26.215 --> 40:27.671
Why us?

40:30.136 --> 40:31.501
Maybe we're being punished.

40:34.015 --> 40:37.178
- Sorry?
- You're good police, Linda...

40:41.689 --> 40:46.149
but there's a lot I've tried
to protect you from about this place.

40:46.361 --> 40:47.851
Like what?

40:56.037 --> 40:57.868
[DUKE SIGHS]

40:58.873 --> 40:59.953
[DOME HUMMING]

41:02.043 --> 41:04.500
A little over a year ago,
I was approached about...

41:04.712 --> 41:05.872
[DOME HUMMING]

41:06.297 --> 41:07.457
[DUKE GRUNTS]

41:09.842 --> 41:11.673
[GRUNTING]

41:12.220 --> 41:13.801
Duke.

41:14.013 --> 41:16.220
- It's my chest.
- Duke, iS it your pacemaker?

41:16.766 --> 41:18.347
Ah! NO! Don't!

41:18.893 --> 41:20.849
Duke. Duke.

41:21.229 --> 41:22.309
Help!

41:22.981 --> 41:26.348
Officer down! Officer down! Help!

41:26.609 --> 41:29.442
Duke, come on. Stay with me, Duke.
Duke, stay with me.

41:29.654 --> 41:31.485
Help uS!

41:34.909 --> 41:36.900
[LINDA SPEAKING INAUDIBLY]

41:37.996 --> 41:38.985
[SOLDIER SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

41:39.247 --> 41:40.578
REPORTER 1:
We 've Spoken with the government,

41:40.790 --> 41:42.030
law enforcement, the military.

41:42.166 --> 41:44.452
No one has any idea
what's going on.

41:44.669 --> 41:46.000
The closest I can come
to an answer

41:46.254 --> 41:49.246
is to Share with you the words
of one scientist we Spoke to today.

41:49.424 --> 41:51.039
REPORTER 2:
He told us, and / quote:

41:51.259 --> 41:54.547
"This is an unparalleled
event in human history. "

41:54.762 --> 41:58.220
Those are not the words of comfort,
not to the nation or the world.

41:58.433 --> 42:00.674
REPORTER 1: Certainly not to
the people of Chester's Mill,

42:00.893 --> 42:03.760
who appear to be trapped,
at least for now.
